Triple layer cloth masks are acceptable. You can also wear a surgical mask under a cloth mask. You can cut a surgical mask to use as a filter in a cloth mask. https://t.co/7V0D7BO8RV
Another thing we do, is we sing, but using Sign Language. So we have songs but we use youtube videos with te reo and NZSL, and we also do dances (Like 35)

I also give the class 'wero' points for dealing with masks. So I acknowledge that it is hard. This isn't about bribing kids or behavioural modification- it's about them SEEING that I see their effort, and acknowledge it.

When discussing behaviour, I try to focus on how we can help each other because we are wearing masks. Having a talking stick or rolling a ball is handy to ensure- ideas like "The mana is with the speaker".
Not just because of masks, but in general, using my voice has been an issue.

When my kids put their masks on I offer them a mint beforehand. If they suck on something it can lubricate their throat. It can also reduce anxiety.
We talk about how they are one way of keeping people safer. We use hanitiser. We keep our distance- "nobody needs to smell what you had for breakfast!"
We made posters to encourage children to wear them. There are stories you can read about wearing masks- all sorts of professions wear masks.
Auckland teachers and children have been wearing masks already in class. I bought disposable masks as spares, and my school got them in for us and they bought child masks.

Meanwhile, if you are the subject of hate or racism, and you want to be angry, you have every bloody right and if I see your comment I will totally uplift YOU rather than the nasty people. I will agree with you, back you up, love your comment, and totally tautoko your anger.

Algorithms will make misinformation and racism 'relevant' if a lot of people interact with them- even just to laugh or mock. So if you're interested in promoting a better experience, find the comments that aren't divisive or inflammatory and uplift and interact

Again, this is not to tell you to interact or not- but if you see, for instance, racism on a post, make a statement uplifting the ethnic group and uplift other statements that support that group, and get your friends to add their likes to the statements that are not racist.

One thing you can do when you see misinformation in comments, is to think of how the algorithm works. Making your OWN comment doesn't draw interactions to misinformation. You can also like or interact positively with people you agree with to uplift the factual statements.

@thejaysmithnz I've been taking a break from my meds but you reminded me to take mine today. Sometimes I really struggle to make decisions or look after myself when I haven't taken them, and so if I go back on it, I have more energy at the end of the day to manage stuff.
So please take my advice with a grain of salt- this isn't my advice, but these resources have helped me to show empathy and compassion without invalidating evidence or other people.

I kinda feel like they took one look at me and decided I was an easy mark. I'm not an easy mark- I'm just an older, non binary, grey haired person who wants to know the deal before I book the appointment. It just seems weird to me, is all.
So all of this is to ask: Do you sometimes feel like grey hair is an indication of someone being intolerant or stupid or rude?

I fully respect hair stylists because their expertise is next level. Me, I can't even handle my wavy hair. It often looks like shit, but that doesn't mean I won't take good advice, pay well for it, and be respectful in the chair.
At that point, I booked in with the top salon, cancelled the other appointment, and paid for the wonderful products I wanted from a store I trusted.
Then I attended the other consult at a very good salon and got a quote for : $230.

I thought I was just out of touch but previously, I've paid around the $200 to $250 mark. He also was quite insistent that I needed a cut (I've just had one from a curl specialist.) I booked in but also booked a consult with someone else.

At this stage he went to the desk to write up a quote. I heard the other person reminding him to 'add extra because of the different colours.' So he returns with a quote of $360 for my medium to short hair, plus extra for products.

I eventually discussed my hair colour. He insisted on bleaching my hair. I said I simply wanted the colour. He gave me a lecture about how my hair colour would look. Dear reader, the hair colour I had from a year ago is LITERALLY still in my hair.

Grey haired people: do you feel like you are treated like an idiot sometimes?

The other day I went for a colour consult because, even though I have grey hair, I do like to be a bit less of a boring sh!t than I was in my younger years.

If you've ever done Yin Yoga you'll hear a lot about releasing fascia. I've automatically been doing Yin without realising why I felt the need. When they talk about holding emotion in the hips, I could literally see if happening

One thing I'm learning is that when under huge stress, getting a weekly massage can help. So I have heard that the fascia, or connective tissue surrounding the muscle, can hold trauma, and specific techniques release it

There's a lot of research about trauma that I have not read but honestly, so much trauma is minimalised or called 'minor' when trauma is, well, trauma. Work related? Still trauma. Mother completely nasty? Trauma. I'm not saying you can't escape, I'm saying don't underestimate it.

Right wing groups are adept at framing messages to encourage people to their way of thinking, and it is frightening how often some of that language is visible on news facebook pages.

In particular, when I see reactions to news articles on social media, specifically facebook, I see people triggered to comment with extrinsic values because they are unaware of how the headline has influenced them.

There are a lot of ways articles in mainstream media feed into racism and nationalism. Opinion pieces are one way, but some issues are with how headlines are framed and the language chosen. Once you learn about framing messages, you can't unsee it when you read the news

If there's a sharp division between people 'used to working with news' and those who don't, it suggests people are not adept at critical thought processes, meaning our media can more easily get away with irresponsible reporting

So many articles in the news use language promoting extrinsic values that divide people and encourage selfishness, and we're not even aware it's happening. We need to critically evaluate our media as much as they evaluate government.

Black Lives Matter.

I know it's made a difference to let people know they are heard and that the injustice is seen and that we support a movement to ensure justice is served. People shouldn't have to protest over and over again. We know this is wrong.

In this age, when Covid19 is an issue and so is systemic injustice and violence and racism, it's still just as important to just stand in solidarity with people who are being oppressed. I went to listen. It's my job to speak up when I'm in a position to do so.

People were trying to socially distance and being told to get into the square instead- keep this in mind when you go off about how people didn't care. They did care; I even said I wanted to socially distance and wouldn't move in. People weren't given a choice.

As for ignorance, it's impossible to be protesting for something on the other side of the world without having an understanding of how you don't have to be personally affected to stand up against injustice.

So we are in a professional setting, having this awkward as all hell conversation but I wasn't backing down. He said, well it was ignorant and rude. Dude, all protests are rude, and they are rude because systemic injustice uses politeness to silence.

However then the conversation turned to "They don't care about George Floyd". I heard the othering in that statement, so I challenged it. I asked if he'd seen the footage of the protests where tensions were escalated instead of deescalated? He hadn't.

As a military brat I know there's a lot of authority in a uniform, and there's a professional sense of pride and a family attitude. So mentioning that professionals are trained better than that was important. He agreed he was horrified.

Today there was a police officer at my work so I started to talk to him about the protest and he was like, "What protest?" and then launched into a defence of how it wasn't the knee on the neck, it was the pressure on the back. I'm like, uh, professionals know better.
